00:44:00,760 --> 00:44:03,513
- No ifs, ands or buts.
- We're disoriented.

684
00:44:03,600 --> 00:44:05,955
- And demented.
- And a little nuts.

685
00:44:08,480 --> 00:44:09,993
<i>Volkswagen car</i>

686
00:44:13,040 --> 00:44:15,156
<i>We were sailing, sailing</i>

687
00:44:15,240 --> 00:44:17,151
<i>The wind was on our side</i>

688
00:44:19,000 --> 00:44:20,831
And then it died.

689
00:44:20,920 --> 00:44:24,037
<i>I got cabin fever</i>
<i>I think I lost my grip</i>

690
00:44:24,120 --> 00:44:28,159
<i>I'd like to get my hands</i>
<i>on whoever wrote this script</i>

691
00:44:28,240 --> 00:44:33,473
<i>I was floating</i>
<i>'neath the tropic moon</i>

692
00:44:33,560 --> 00:44:36,996
<i>And dreaming</i>
<i>of a blue lagoon</i>

693
00:44:37,080 --> 00:44:40,356
<i>Now I'm as crazy as a loon</i>

694
00:44:40,440 --> 00:44:44,115
<i>Cabin fever</i>
<i>has ravaged all aboard</i>

695
00:44:44,200 --> 00:44:47,397
<i>This one small vessel</i>
<i>has become a floating psycho ward</i>

696
00:44:47,480 --> 00:44:51,234
<i>We were sailing, sailing</i>
<i>heading who knows where</i>

697
00:44:51,320 --> 00:44:54,118
<i>And now though</i>
<i>we're all here</i>

698
00:44:54,200 --> 00:44:57,237
<i>We're not all there</i>

699
00:45:05,400 --> 00:45:07,755
Cabin fever!

700
00:45:08,760 --> 00:45:09,795
- The wind is back.
- What are we doing?

701
00:45:09,880 --> 00:45:12,189
What's goin' on here?

702
00:45:12,280 --> 00:45:14,589
- What was that?
- I feel like such a fool.

703
00:45:14,680 --> 00:45:18,116
- Yeah, me too.
- I hope nobody saw that. Embarrassing.

704
00:45:18,200 --> 00:45:20,111
- Get us outta here! Help!
- We didn't hit him!

705
00:45:20,200 --> 00:45:22,760
Come on. Let us out.
We was only joking.

706
00:45:24,440 --> 00:45:27,398
- Hey, Long John!
Hey, get us outta here!

707
00:45:27,480 --> 00:45:29,311
- Hey-ey-ey, Polly.
- What?

708
00:45:29,400 --> 00:45:32,676
- What was that song that just happened?
- What are you talkin' about?

709
00:45:32,760 --> 00:45:35,832
You know.
<i>Cabin Fever</i>

710
00:45:35,920 --> 00:45:38,912
- That.
- You see,John?

711
00:45:39,000 --> 00:45:42,117
You gotta get us outta here now!
Clueless is startin' to go crackers!

712
00:45:44,240 --> 00:45:46,071
Here you go.

713
00:45:46,160 --> 00:45:49,789
- Your bread and water for today.
- But I ordered shrimp scampi.

714
00:45:49,880 --> 00:45:53,668
It's more than you deserve,
ya villainous dogs!

715
00:45:53,760 --> 00:45:55,352
Oh,Jim.

716
00:45:55,440 --> 00:45:58,193
By rights,
I should be locked up too...

717
00:45:58,280 --> 00:46:00,999
for lettin' thieves like them
aboard this ship.

718
00:46:01,080 --> 00:46:03,230
Oh, it chills me...

719
00:46:03,320 --> 00:46:06,118
to think that they almost
killed your little friends...

720
00:46:06,200 --> 00:46:08,350
looking for some
daft treasure map.

721
00:46:08,440 --> 00:46:12,752
None of this would've happened if I'd
have given Captain Smollet the--

722
00:46:15,320 --> 00:46:17,390
What, lad?

723
00:46:17,480 --> 00:46:20,631
I'm not really sure I should be talking
about this with you or with anyone.

724
00:46:20,720 --> 00:46:25,396
You mean, you've really
got a treasure map?

725
00:46:25,480 --> 00:46:29,155
Not any more. Mr Arrow took it and
locked it up in the captain's cabin.

726
00:46:29,240 --> 00:46:31,071
You must promise
to keep it a secret.

727
00:46:31,160 --> 00:46:35,233
Don't bother your head about that.
You've only told old Long John.

728
00:46:35,320 --> 00:46:37,595
Now, you run along
and do your chores. Go on.

729
00:46:37,680 --> 00:46:39,557
Go on.

730
00:47:02,760 --> 00:47:04,716
Safely now. Safely.

731
00:47:08,360 --> 00:47:10,271
Steady as she goes.

732
00:47:13,200 --> 00:47:15,839
Oh. Mr Silver, good evening.

733
00:47:15,920 --> 00:47:18,195
Wicked fog tonight, sir.

734
00:47:18,280 --> 00:47:21,431
Reminds me of the night
we ran aground off the pampas.

735
00:47:21,520 --> 00:47:24,080
Half the crew drowned
in leaky lifeboats.

736
00:47:24,160 --> 00:47:25,991
Ah, it were
a terrible shame.

737
00:47:26,080 --> 00:47:29,231
- Leaky lifeboats?
- Oh, a common occurrence, sir.

738
00:47:29,320 --> 00:47:32,312
A little-used piece of equipment
falls into disrepair...

739
00:47:32,400 --> 00:47:36,359
- and becomes, shall we say--
- Unsafe?

740
00:47:36,440 --> 00:47:40,035
Oh, I'm not sayin'
our lifeboats are unsafe, sir.

741
00:47:40,120 --> 00:47:44,113
I'm not sayin'
we got problems--

742
00:47:44,200 --> 00:47:45,633
Still--

743
00:47:47,640 --> 00:47:48,709
Hmm. Hmm.

744
00:47:48,800 --> 00:47:52,998
The caulking appears tight.
No dampness under the gunwale.

745
00:47:53,080 --> 00:47:54,877
This one seems seaworthy.

746
00:47:54,960 --> 00:47:59,272
Well, sir, they do, of course, until
you get them out in the open ocean.

747
00:48:00,800 --> 00:48:03,189
- Cast me off, Mr Silver.
- Oh, yes, sir.

748
00:48:03,280 --> 00:48:08,513
Oh, sir, is there anything I can
hold for you for safekeeping?

749
00:48:08,600 --> 00:48:11,114
Your hat? Your coat?

750
00:48:11,200 --> 00:48:14,590
- Your keys?
- Hmm? My keys?

751
00:48:14,680 --> 00:48:19,674
Of course. If they were to fall
overboard, it would be disastrous.

752
00:48:19,760 --> 00:48:22,558
Oh, that it would, sir.

753
00:48:25,080 --> 00:48:26,638
Cast me off, Mr Silver!

754
00:48:26,720 --> 00:48:28,199
Aye, aye, sir!

755
00:48:29,360 --> 00:48:31,476
Thank you, Mr Silver.

756
00:48:31,560 --> 00:48:33,915
Just doin' my duty, sir.

757
00:48:38,320 --> 00:48:39,958
Oh, yes,John.

758
00:48:41,680 --> 00:48:44,638
Man overboard!

759
00:48:49,160 --> 00:48:50,070
Yes.

760
00:48:50,160 --> 00:48:51,991
- I'm sorry, sir.
- Wha--

761
00:48:52,080 --> 00:48:54,833
Mr Arrow's gone overboard,
and...

762
00:48:54,920 --> 00:48:57,388
all we found was his hat!

763
00:48:57,480 --> 00:48:59,198
Oh, no.

764
00:49:05,560 --> 00:49:10,395
And so, my friends, the sea has claimed
another loyal officer and friend.

765
00:49:10,480 --> 00:49:12,391
- This was a person who served--
- I got it! I got it!

766
00:49:12,480 --> 00:49:14,391
Okay, after you, Monty.

767
00:49:14,480 --> 00:49:17,119
- No, after you.
- Will you just come on.

768
00:49:17,200 --> 00:49:19,668
Mr Samuel Arrow,
a wonderful man who...

769
00:49:19,760 --> 00:49:22,718
used to get us up from our beds
before dawn for a good flossing.

770
00:49:24,840 --> 00:49:27,434
- Okay, okay. Now, spread out
and find the map.

771
00:49:27,520 --> 00:49:32,071
May the wind be ever at your back,
Samuel Arrow. Rest in peace, my friend.

772
00:49:32,160 --> 00:49:34,720
- Amen.
- Amen.

773
00:49:37,120 --> 00:49:39,236
Shh.

774
00:49:40,800 --> 00:49:43,189
- See? See?
- Wait. Open it. Open it.

775
00:49:43,280 --> 00:49:46,875
No, no, no, we gotta take it
to Long John. Come on.

776
00:49:54,320 --> 00:49:56,151
This apple has a worm in it.

777
00:49:56,240 --> 00:49:59,357
That's not a worm.
That's my tail.

778
00:49:59,440 --> 00:50:01,351
What's wrong?

779
00:50:02,440 --> 00:50:06,149
- It just feels so weird.
- You mean, that Mr Arrow's dead?

780
00:50:06,240 --> 00:50:10,916
Yeah, that, and my pants
are filled with starfish.

781
00:50:11,000 --> 00:50:13,070
You and your hobbies!

782
00:50:13,160 --> 00:50:15,355
Rizzo!

783
00:50:15,440 --> 00:50:18,716
-Jim, we've missed you! Climb in!
- Can't. I'm doing my chores.

784
00:50:18,800 --> 00:50:21,997
- Oh, come on. Share an apple.
- Yeah, come on!

785
00:50:25,440 --> 00:50:29,752
- Anyway, here's the plan.
- I say we should kill that captain now.

786
00:50:29,840 --> 00:50:33,389
- And then we'll get
that twit of a bear!

787
00:50:34,480 --> 00:50:36,391
Oh, hi, Long John.

788
00:50:38,480 --> 00:50:43,349
I'm an easy man.
A gentlemen of fortune, says most.

789
00:50:43,440 --> 00:50:46,637
But it makes me sick at heart
to sail with the likes of you.

790
00:50:47,920 --> 00:50:50,070
Now, get this straight.

791
00:50:50,160 --> 00:50:53,277
If anyone mutinies
before I says so...

792
00:50:53,360 --> 00:50:57,433
I'll throw you overboard
like I did that scurvy mate Mr Arrow!

793
00:50:57,520 --> 00:51:02,230
I says, let the captain
steer us closer to the island.

794
00:51:02,320 --> 00:51:04,231
I've got the lad's
treasure map now.

795
00:51:04,320 --> 00:51:06,550
When the time is ripe,
we'll kill 'em all!

796
00:51:06,640 --> 00:51:10,599
- That's what I said!
- That's what I said!

797
00:51:10,680 --> 00:51:14,070
- Land ho!
- Come on, lads! Let's go!

798
00:51:14,160 --> 00:51:16,071
Yea! Land ho!

799
00:51:19,680 --> 00:51:22,558
Oh, my goodness.

800
00:51:25,760 --> 00:51:27,318
Land ho!

801
00:51:28,720 --> 00:51:30,597
Beachfront property!

802
00:51:30,680 --> 00:51:32,511
Retirement estates!

803
00:51:32,600 --> 00:51:34,158
- Bikinis!
- Bikinis!

804
00:51:35,200 --> 00:51:37,839
Throw the mainsail!
Drop anchor!

805
00:51:37,920 --> 00:51:40,832
Bring her up
hard of starboard, helmsman.

806
00:51:48,440 --> 00:51:50,556
Bring those barrels
over here, lads!

807
00:51:51,800 --> 00:51:53,791
Helmsman, give a hand
with the longboats.

808
00:51:53,880 --> 00:51:56,189
- Captain, may I speak with you?
- I'm sort of busy right now,Jim.

809
00:51:56,280 --> 00:51:59,875
But, Captain, we just heard.
Long John is planning a mutiny,

810
00:51:59,960 --> 00:52:01,951
- Yeah.
- I see.

811
00:52:02,040 --> 00:52:04,634
- Mr Silver?
- Aye, aye, Cap'n!

812
00:52:04,720 --> 00:52:06,995
Mr Silver, I want you
to take the crew ashore at once.

813
00:52:07,080 --> 00:52:09,594
We need water and provisions.
Take as long as you want.

814
00:52:11,520 --> 00:52:14,637
Sir! 'Tis a task to my liking, sir.
That it is!

815
00:52:14,720 --> 00:52:18,110
- Quickly, boys. Gather the officers
and meet me in my quarters. Quickly.

816
00:52:19,400 --> 00:52:21,550
This is a lucky break.
Captain lettin' us go ashore.

817
00:52:21,640 --> 00:52:23,517
Us with the map and all.

818
00:52:23,600 --> 00:52:26,273
It's like giving the treasure to us
on a silver platter.

819
00:52:26,360 --> 00:52:31,036
Aye, that it is, Polly.
Never trust a silver platter.

820
00:52:35,560 --> 00:52:37,437
Follow me, Beakie. Come along.

821
00:52:39,160 --> 00:52:40,229
Jim, lad!

822
00:52:40,320 --> 00:52:44,154
There's room in the boat for one more.
Come along for an adventure.

823
00:52:44,240 --> 00:52:47,516
- I-I can't. The captain wants me.
- Oh, what a shame!

824
00:52:47,600 --> 00:52:49,955
I'll miss you, lad.
That I will.

825
00:52:50,040 --> 00:52:54,636
Um,Jim! I seem to have
left my crutch on board.

826
00:52:54,720 --> 00:52:56,790
Hand it to me like
a good lad, will ya?

827
00:52:59,920 --> 00:53:01,399
There's a good boy.

828
00:53:03,200 --> 00:53:05,998
Have to be a bit closer than that.
Can't reach it from there.

829
00:53:06,680 --> 00:53:08,830
- Oh!
- Oh! Ah!

830
00:53:08,920 --> 00:53:11,036
Cast away, men!
Be quick now!

831
00:53:11,120 --> 00:53:13,270
Go, go, go!
Don't splash!

832
00:53:16,080 --> 00:53:17,354
The plan is simple.

833
00:53:17,440 --> 00:53:20,512
Once the pirates are ashore,
we set sail and return in a year or so.

834
00:53:20,600 --> 00:53:23,672
- By then, all the fight
should be out of'em.

835
00:53:23,760 --> 00:53:24,988
That's a brilliant plan.

836
00:53:25,080 --> 00:53:27,036
- Except for one thing.
- What's that?

837
00:53:27,120 --> 00:53:29,680
The pirates have Jim!

838
00:53:45,400 --> 00:53:46,594
I'm tired!

839
00:53:46,680 --> 00:53:48,272
- You're what?
- I'm gettin' tired!

840
00:53:48,360 --> 00:53:51,830
- He says go faster.
- I'm gettin' tired!

841
00:54:05,600 --> 00:54:08,353
Hey, man! I can't figure out
what side we're on.

842
00:54:08,440 --> 00:54:11,079
Are we with the pirates
or the frog captain?

843
00:54:11,160 --> 00:54:13,151
Oh, hey, man,
just play the gig.

844
00:54:13,240 --> 00:54:15,356
Never get involved in politics.

845
00:54:15,440 --> 00:54:17,715
Politics!
Politics!

846
00:54:26,520 --> 00:54:28,033
Jim, lad!

847
00:54:35,520 --> 00:54:39,513
Easy,Jim.
'Tis all in good fun.

848
00:54:39,600 --> 00:54:44,230
Pleased I am to initiate you
into our enterprising, um, company.

849
00:54:46,480 --> 00:54:48,675
Which entitles you
to all the benefits thereof.

850
00:54:48,760 --> 00:54:54,232
- But I don't want any benefits.
- This is a one-time

851
00:54:54,320 --> 00:54:58,950
Say no, and I will be forced
to, um, terminate our relationship.

852
00:55:00,480 --> 00:55:04,268
- You're nothing but murdering pirates.
- Pirates!

853
00:55:07,720 --> 00:55:10,314
Pirates. Oh,Jim.

854
00:55:11,480 --> 00:55:13,630
If that's what
you're thinking...

855
00:55:13,720 --> 00:55:15,392
you're dead wrong.

856
00:55:17,280 --> 00:55:19,077
<i>When I was just a lad</i>

857
00:55:19,160 --> 00:55:21,594
<i>Looking for my true vocation</i>

858
00:55:21,680 --> 00:55:23,875
<i>My father said</i>
<i>Now, son, this choice</i>

859
00:55:23,960 --> 00:55:26,315
<i>Deserves deliberation</i>

860
00:55:26,400 --> 00:55:28,470
<i>Though you could be a doctor</i>

861
00:55:28,560 --> 00:55:30,949
<i>Or perhaps a financier</i>

862
00:55:31,040 --> 00:55:35,352
<i>My boy, why not consider</i>
<i>a more challenging career</i>

863
00:55:35,440 --> 00:55:36,793
<i>Hey, ho, ho</i>

864
00:55:36,880 --> 00:55:39,235
- <i>You'll cruise to foreign shores</i>
- Sing it, lads!

865
00:55:39,320 --> 00:55:42,915
<i>-And you'll keep your mind and body</i>
<i>sound by working out of doors</i>

866
00:55:43,000 --> 00:55:46,549
<i>True friendship and adventure</i>
<i>are what we can't live without</i>

867
00:55:46,640 --> 00:55:52,078
<i>-And when you're</i>
<i>a professional pirate</i>

868
00:55:52,160 --> 00:55:56,950
Upstage, lads!
This is my only number.

869
00:55:57,040 --> 00:56:01,431
<i>Now take Sir Francis Drake</i>
<i>The Spanish all despise him</i>

870
00:56:01,520 --> 00:56:06,310
<i>But to the British he's a hero</i>
<i>and they idolize him</i>

871
00:56:06,400 --> 00:56:08,595
<i>It's how you look at buccaneers</i>

872
00:56:08,680 --> 00:56:10,591
<i>That makes them bad or good</i>

873
00:56:10,680 --> 00:56:14,514
<i>And I see us as members</i>
<i>of a noble brotherhood</i>

874
00:56:14,600 --> 00:56:16,352
- Hup!
- <i>Hey, ho, ho</i>

875
00:56:16,440 --> 00:56:19,159
- Oh, I love it!
- <i>We're honourable men</i>

876
00:56:19,240 --> 00:56:22,550
<i>And before we lose our tempers</i>
<i>we will always count to ten</i>

877
00:56:22,640 --> 00:56:26,394
<i>On occasion there may be</i>
<i>someone you have to execute</i>

878
00:56:26,480 --> 00:56:30,393
<i>But when you're</i>
<i>a professional pirate</i>

879
00:56:30,480 --> 00:56:32,471
<i>You don't have</i>
<i>to wear a suit</i>

880
00:56:33,760 --> 00:56:38,436
- What?
<i>- I could have been a surgeon</i>

881
00:56:38,520 --> 00:56:42,433
<i>I could have been a lawyer</i>
<i>but I just had too much heart</i>

882
00:56:42,520 --> 00:56:45,318
<i>I could have been in politics</i>

883
00:56:45,400 --> 00:56:49,439
<i>'Cause I've always been</i>
<i>a big spender</i>

884
00:56:49,520 --> 00:56:53,559
<i>And me, I could have been</i>
<i>a contender</i>

885
00:56:56,360 --> 00:56:58,635
<i>Some say that pirates steal</i>

886
00:56:58,720 --> 00:57:01,280
<i>And should be feared and hated</i>

887
00:57:01,360 --> 00:57:03,669
<i>I say we're victims</i>
<i>of bad press</i>

888
00:57:03,760 --> 00:57:05,910
<i>It's all exaggerated</i>

889
00:57:06,000 --> 00:57:08,355
<i>We'd never stab you</i>
<i>in the back</i>

890
00:57:08,440 --> 00:57:10,556
<i>We'd never lie or cheat</i>

891
00:57:10,640 --> 00:57:12,790
<i>We'rejust about the nicest guys</i>

892
00:57:12,880 --> 00:57:15,110
<i>You'd ever want to meet</i>

893
00:57:15,200 --> 00:57:17,156
Well, look at us,Jim.

894
00:57:17,240 --> 00:57:19,959
We're a festival
of conviviality.

895
00:57:22,200 --> 00:57:22,916
Congeniality.

896
00:57:23,000 --> 00:57:26,913
- That's conviviality, stupid.
- That's what I said.

897
00:57:27,000 --> 00:57:28,558
We're ready, O <i>capitn</i>.

898
00:57:28,640 --> 00:57:32,519
Good. You men guard the ship
while I'm gone. We'll be back

899
00:57:32,600 --> 00:57:34,716
- Aye, aye, Captain.
- Cast off, Mr Beaker.

900
00:57:36,920 --> 00:57:39,309
Thanks for coming along, men.

901
00:57:39,400 --> 00:57:42,472
- Are you kidding? Jim is family.
- Yeah.

902
00:57:43,680 --> 00:57:45,636
Tell the truth, lad.

903
00:57:45,720 --> 00:57:47,950
Do you really think the captain
and the squire...

904
00:57:48,040 --> 00:57:50,713
are planning to share the treasure
with the likes of us?

905
00:57:52,040 --> 00:57:53,758
Can't hear ya.

906
00:57:53,840 --> 00:57:55,558
No?

907
00:57:55,640 --> 00:57:57,949
And we being
the rightful owners.

908
00:57:58,040 --> 00:58:02,670
Flint's own crew, who shed
our blood getting it here!

909
00:58:05,080 --> 00:58:06,718
